<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=15979&amp;p=196635#p196635</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=15979&amp;p=196635#p196635"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Comparative sprite capacity of 3rd and 4th gen consoles]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=15979&amp;p=196635#p196635"><![CDATA[
Perhaps the smaller res (304x224) was more compatible with marginal monitors, particularly aging MVS monitors and the TVs used with the AES.<br /><br />If you compare the AES's output timing to that of a standard TV, you find that only 315x240 pixels are in the 4:3 frame, the rest in what Rec. 601 calls the &quot;nominal analog blanking&quot; area. (The AES pixel aspect ratio is 65:64.) Assuming 3.5% overscan on all sides, you end up with close to 64/65*.93*320 by .93*240 = 293x223 visible.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu May 25, 2017 12:06 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
