<div class="quotetitle">lidnariq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><em>edit2:</em> During the 5th console generation, SVGA cards actually grew support for one sprite (i.e. composited dynamically during refresh), intended for the mouse cursor.<br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Amiga<br /></div>OCS or AGA?</div>That is OCS , although the bolting might be ECS<br /><br />AGA has 32 or 64 wide sprites ( all must be the same width), hires or superhires resolutions ( as sprite resolution and colours are independent of &quot;window&quot; resolution ), you can have 2 palletes were odd sprites are one and even is another.<br />You can have Vertical doubling ( each line is repeated twice, useful for interlace modes)<br />You can reuse the same sprite again on the same X line ( you can do it on ECS, but on AGA it is without cleaver timings, tricks etc )<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=8250">Oziphantom</a> — Wed May 24, 2017 11:10 pm</p><hr />
